Collection Description
## Collection Description â€“ API Testing Final Project (DummyJSON) This collection represents the **API Testing Final Project**, implemented using **Postman** and based on the **DummyJSON API**. The purpose of this collection is to validate the functionality, reliability, and behavior of multiple API endpoints through **positive and negative test scenarios**, following Quality Assurance best practices. --- ### Authentication Authentication endpoints are tested to ensure secure access and proper session handling. This includes validating successful login, token generation, token refresh functionality, and system behavior when invalid or unauthorized requests are sent. --- ### Products Product-related endpoints are tested to verify correct retrieval, creation, updating, and deletion of products. Both functional scenarios and validation-related edge cases are covered to ensure data consistency and expected API behavior. --- ### Product Categories Category endpoints are tested to validate category retrieval in different formats and to ensure correct filtering of products by category. Dynamic data handling is applied to avoid hard-coded values. --- ### Carts Cart endpoints are tested to validate cart creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion operations. The tests ensure correct linkage between users, products, and cart calculations such as totals and quantities. --- ### Negative Scenarios Negative test cases are included to evaluate how the API handles invalid input, unauthorized access, non-existent resources, and missing required data. Some negative tests intentionally fail to highlight **validation gaps** and potential data integrity issues within the API. --- ### Testing Approach - Automated assertions are implemented using Postman test scripts. - Environment variables are used for dynamic data handling (tokens, IDs). - Response validation includes status codes, response format, data structure, and performance checks. - Observed API limitations are documented as part of the testing results. --- ### Conclusion This collection demonstrates a structured and realistic API testing approach, combining functional validation with negative testing to reflect real-world Quality Assurance practices. ---

Request Description
This request authenticates a valid user using the DummyJSON authentication endpoint. A random valid user is selected from a predefined list of credentials provided by DummyJSON documentation. The request sends the username and password to obtain an access token and refresh token. **Validations performed:** - Verify that the API responds with HTTP 200. - Verify that the response is returned in JSON format. - Verify that an access token is returned. - Verify that a refresh token is returned. - Store the access token and refresh token as environment variables for use in protected endpoints.
